        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-6">
            <b class="font-bold">Landscape mode</b>
          </td>
          <td class="text-center py-6 text-green-700">Yes</td>
          <td class="text-center py-6 text-green-700">Yes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-6">
            <b class="font-bold">Apple Watch</b>
          </td>
          <td class="text-center py-6 text-red-700">No</td>
          <td class="text-center py-6 text-red-700">No</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-6">
            <b class="font-bold">Languages</b>
          </td>
          <td class="text-center py-6">6</td>
          <td class="text-center py-6">1</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-6">
            <b class="font-bold">App Store rating</b>
          </td>
          <td class="text-center py-6">4.9 stars</td>
          <td class="text-center py-6">4.8 stars</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-sans font-bold mt-16 mb-4">
        Who should choose Box Timer?
      </h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        Box Timer is the better choice for almost any athlete who trains
        regularly. The most obvious reason: Tabata Stopwatch Pro's free tier
        allows only one workout every seven days. That is not a countdown timer
        for most people — it is a demo. If you train four or five times a week
        and do not want to pay $19.99 for the pro unlock, Box Timer is the
        practical choice.
      </p>
      <p class="mb-4">
        Box Timer also supports the full range of CrossFit WOD formats. Tabata
        Stopwatch Pro focuses on Tabata and custom intervals — AMRAP, EMOM, and
        For Time are not available. Athletes who program a mix of WOD types will
        need Box Timer or a different app to fill those gaps.
      </p>
      <p class="mb-4">
        The gym-style digital display and loud round-transition beeps make Box
        Timer a natural fit for garage gym athletes who need a clock they can
        read from a distance while moving a barbell.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-sans font-bold mt-16 mb-4">
        Who should choose Tabata Stopwatch Pro?
      </h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        Tabata Stopwatch Pro has a distinctive visual approach: the display uses
        color to represent energy levels during intervals, shifting from green
        to red as each work period progresses. Combined with voice
        announcements, it creates a sensory experience designed to keep athletes
        at maximum effort during high-intensity Tabata work.
      </p>
      <p class="mb-4">
        Apple Health integration is a genuine advantage if you track your
        workouts in the Health app alongside other fitness data. For athletes
        building a long-term training log across different apps, having interval
        sessions automatically logged in Health adds value.
      </p>
      <p class="mb-4">
        At $19.99 for the pro version, Tabata Stopwatch Pro is a meaningful
        investment compared to Box Timer's free pricing. It makes sense for a
        dedicated Tabata practitioner who values the voice guidance and energy
        visualization and trains specifically within that protocol.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-sans font-bold mt-16 mb-4">
        Setup comparison: Tabata
      </h2>
      <p class="mb-2">
        For a standard Tabata (8 rounds of 20 seconds work, 10 seconds rest):
      </p>
      <p class="mb-2"><strong>Box Timer</strong></p>
      <ol class="list-decimal list-outside ml-6 space-y-1 mb-6">
        <li>
          Tap <strong>Edit Timer</strong> and select <strong>Interval</strong>
        </li>
        <li>
          Set <strong>Rounds</strong> to 8, <strong>Work</strong> to 0:20, <strong
            >Rest</strong
          > to 0:10
        </li>
        <li>Tap <strong>Save</strong>, then <strong>Start</strong></li>
      </ol>
      <p class="mb-2"><strong>Tabata Stopwatch Pro</strong></p>
      <ol class="list-decimal list-outside ml-6 space-y-1 mb-6">
        <li>Select a Tabata preset</li>
        <li>Configure rounds and interval durations if adjusting defaults</li>
        <li>Tap <strong>Start</strong></li>
      </ol>
      <p class="mb-4">
        Both apps get you into a Tabata quickly. Tabata Stopwatch Pro's
        color-shifting display and voice announcements provide a richer
        in-workout experience once running. Box Timer's setup is straightforward
        and the beeps are sufficient for most athletes without the visual color
        feedback.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-sans font-bold mt-16 mb-4">Pricing</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        Box Timer is free — no ads, no usage limits, no in-app purchases.
      </p>
      <p class="mb-4">
        Tabata Stopwatch Pro offers a free tier that is severely restricted: one
        workout every seven days with ads. The pro unlock is a one-time purchase
        of $19.99 that removes limits and adds voice announcements and
        additional features. Verify current pricing in the App Store.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-sans font-bold mt-16 mb-4">Verdict</h2>
      <p class="mb-4">
        For most athletes, the choice is straightforward: Box Timer is free,
        unlimited, and covers more WOD formats. Tabata Stopwatch Pro's free tier
        is too restricted to be useful for regular training without upgrading.
      </p>
      <p class="mb-4">
        If you are a serious Tabata practitioner who trains with that specific
        protocol regularly and wants voice coaching with Apple Health logging,
        Tabata Stopwatch Pro's $19.99 pro unlock is worth evaluating. For
        everyone else, Box Timer is the practical, cost-free choice.
      </p>

      <p class="mt-16">
